## Behavior Notes

- `phala_app` is the main lifecycle resource for Phala Cloud deployments.
- `replicas` scales one app definition horizontally across multiple **anonymous** CVMs (all share the parent app's name). Use for stateless replica sets.
- For stateful replica sets with stable per-member identity (Consul, Patroni, etcd, Kafka, etc.), declare `members` and pair `phala_app` with `phala_app_instance`. See [`phala_app_instance`](app_instance.md) for the full MIG-style pattern.
- `docker_compose`, runtime visibility flags, and encrypted environment updates are applied across the app.
- `instances` exposes the current per-CVM member view without introducing backend-native ordinals.
- `wait_for_ready = true` waits until the app reports running replicas before returning.
- `ssh_authorized_keys`, `storage_fs`, placement fields, and deterministic identity inputs can affect replacement behavior; check the schema details below before changing them in-place.

## MIG-mode validation

When `members` is set, the provider enforces two invariants at plan time:

1. `name` must be one of `members` — otherwise the bootstrap CVM has nothing to adopt it and would become an unreferenced extra under the app.
2. `replicas` must be unset or exactly 1 — the legacy anonymous-replica path (`/cvms/{src}/replicas`) conflicts with named slots and would silently create unnamed duplicates.

Downstream `phala_app_instance` resources should set `for_each = toset(phala_app.foo.members)` so the slot list stays a single source of truth.

## In-place updates are blocked in members mode

The cloud's per-CVM PATCH endpoints (`/cvms/{id}/docker-compose`, `/envs`, `/os-image`, `/resources`, `/compose_file/provision`) only target a single CVM, and the legacy app-wide fan-out (`/apps/{id}/cvms/{src}/replicas`) is intentionally disabled in members mode because it would silently delete a named slot. Until the cloud exposes an app-revision-aware update endpoint that preserves named slot identity, this provider refuses at plan time to update any of these `phala_app` fields when `members` is set:

`docker_compose`, `pre_launch_script`, `env`, `encrypted_env`, `env_keys`, `env_compose_hash`, `env_transaction_hash`, `image`, `size`, `disk_size`, `public_logs`, `public_sysinfo`, `public_tcbinfo`, `gateway_enabled`, `secure_time`.

Workarounds:
1. Destroy the `phala_app` + matching `phala_app_instance` resources and recreate them with the new compose / env / image.
2. Move per-slot variations to `phala_app_instance.env` (per-slot encrypted env at create time; immutable thereafter).

Adding or removing entries from `members` is still safe (it just spawns or destroys `phala_app_instance` resources). Removing the `members` attribute entirely (transitioning back to anonymous-replicas mode) is **not** safe and is also blocked at plan time — destroy and recreate the app.

